1. Check if Apache Tomcat 9 is present
sudo systemctl restart tomcat
go to localhost:<tomcat_port_no> // to verify tomcat is running
sudo systemctl status tomcat //this should show status active

2. Install JDK and IntelliJ IDEA Ultimate
sudo apt update
sudo apt install openjdk-8-jdk
sudo snap install intellij-idea-ultimate –classic
3. Setting Up Tomcat in IntelliJ IDEA
o Open Settings
File → Settings → Build, Execution, Deployment
o Open Application Servers
On the left side, click: Application Servers
o Add a New Server
Click the ‘+’ icon : Select Tomcat Server
o Select Tomcat Home Directory
In the Tomcat Home field, enter the Tomcat installation path - /opt/tomcat 
If there is Error / Warning then fix Permission Issue in Terminal

Open terminal and run:
sudo chmod -R a+rX /opt/tomcat // givesread and execute permission to all 
users
o Apply and Save
Go back to IntelliJ → Apply → OK
4. Create a Web Application (Server Side) – Calculator Project
o Open IntelliJ IDEA
Go to File → New Project
o Choose Java Enterprise / Jakarta EE
o Project Name: calculator
o On the right side, under templates, choose: Web Application
o Under Application Server, choose: Apache Tomcat (Tomcat 9.0)
o Keep everything else default and click Finish → wait for the project to load
5. Create service package and class
o Under calculator in src/main/java right-click the package com.example.calculator → 
Select New → Java Class → Create a class named OperatorService.java and add 
below code

package com.example.calculator;
import java.util.List;
import javax.jws.WebMethod; 
import javax.jws.WebService;
@WebService
public class OperatorService {
@WebMethod
public int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
@WebMethod
public int sub(int a, int b) { return a - b; }
@WebMethod
public int mul(int a, int b) { return a * b; }
@WebMethod
public int div(int a, int b) { return a / b; }

o Similarly in the same package, create OperatorPublisher.java and add below 
code
package com.example.calculator; 
import javax.xml.ws.Endpoint;
public class OperatorPublisher {
public static void main(String[] args) {
String url = "http://localhost:8085/calculator"; 
Endpoint.publish(url, new OperatorService()); 
System.out.println("Service started at: " + url + "?wsdl");
}
}

6. Set Language Level in Project Structure
o File → Project Structure
o Click Modules on the left side.
o Select your module: calculator
o Sources tab -> Set Language Level -> 8 – Lambdas, type annotations, etc.
o Open Dependencies -> Under Module SDK -> Project SDK (1.8) /Java 1.8
o Click Apply → OK.
7. Set Target Bytecode Version

o File → Settings →Build, Execution, Deployment →Compiler → Java Compiler
o Under Per-module bytecode version → Find your module calculator → Set Target 
bytecode version = 8
o Click Apply → OK.
8. Set Maven Runner JRE (Java 1.8)
o File → Settings → Build, Execution, Deployment → Build Tools → Maven → Runner
o Under JRE -> Java 1.8
o Click Apply → OK.
251100680004
9. Update pom.xml Settings (Set Java Version & Servlet Version)
o In IntelliJ, look at the left navigation panel -> Click to open pom.xml.
o Locate the <properties> section.
o Make sure the versions are set to 1.8 like this :
<properties>
<project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>
<maven.compiler.target>1.8</maven.compiler.target> //change to 1.8
<maven.compiler.source>1.8</maven.compiler.source> // change to 1.8
<junit.version>5.13.2</junit.version>
</properties>
o Scroll to the dependencies section.
o Check the jakarta.servlet-api dependency. Make sure version is: 4.0.4
o If your file had any other version (like 5.x or newer), replace it with 4.0.4.
o After modifying, right-click pom.xml →Maven → Sync Project.
251100680004
10. Run the Web Service (Server Application)
o If HelloServlet.java shows errors -> open file -> Replace all jakarta.servlet.* with
javax.servlet.*
o Build → Rebuild Project
o Open class OperatorPublisher.java → Run 'OperatorPublisher'
o Check Console Output :
Service started at http://localhost:8085/calculator
o Access the WSDL in Browser : open http://localhost:8085/calculator?wsdl
o If the WSDL loads successfully -
Your web service is deployed and running correctly and you will get a page 
pasted below.


11. Create a Client Application - Client Project
o Open IntelliJ IDEA
Go to File → New Project
o Do NOT select Java Enterprise / Jakarta EE. -> Choose Java (simple Java project).
o Project Name: client -> keep default -> Click Finish -> Open in New Window.
(Do not close the server project.)

o Generate Client Proxy Classes inside src/com/example/client using wsimport
Open system Terminal -> Change directory to the client src folder:
cd /IdeaProjects/client/src/
Run the wsimport command:
wsimport -keep -p com.example.client http://localhost:8085/calculator?wsdl
o Create Client File 
client
└ ── src
└ ── com
└ ── example
└ ── client
Right-click com.example.client → New → Java Class → TestOperatorClient
Add the following code:
package com.example.client; 
public class TestOperatorClient {
public static void main(String[] args) {
OperatorServiceService service = new OperatorServiceService(); 
OperatorService port = service.getOperatorServicePort();
System.out.println("Add: " + port.add(20, 5)); 
System.out.println("Sub: " + port.sub(20, 5)); 
System.out.println("Mul: " + port.mul(20, 5)); 
System.out.println("Div: " + port.div(20, 5));
}
}

12. Run the Client Application
Ensure your server project (OperatorPublisher) is still running.
In client project -> right-click TestOperatorClient.java. 
Select Run 'TestOperatorClient'.
Output : will get the following:
Add: 25
Sub: 15
Mul: 1
